spans.text: Beneath the fern the moorcock sleeps , And twisted adders lie
" Have ! see , across the dreary waste , A moving form
the youthful glow And greeting smile
I will follow thee , And share thy hapless doom
little power To ease another's pain
Nor shall these dim and weary eyes Behold tomorrow's sun
LOUD roars the wind that shakes the wall
no peace But with the morning sun , " Vain hope ! the guilty never rest
is a midnight in the breast No morn shall ever cheer
his head ; An easy lair the guiltless find Upon the hardest bed
whatever the boldest can , Then why this childish dread ?
— " At this dread hour Why dost thou haunt the night
Why dost thou haunt the night
wave That fatal shaft of strife
Which shook the floor and wall
dwells his mind with gloomy fears , And murdered Edward glares
The ghost of some departed friend
the hall the pale lamp gleams Upon my father's arms ; My soul
I but see that face again
that voice which soothed my pain
silent by the wall : My nights
some delusion of the mind My senses
with the softly trembling wire Surrounding echoes mourned
fold thee to my heart , If aught of form thou hast
fainter grew , And long and sadly mourned , And softly sighed a long adieu , And never more returned
Thick as the gloom of night , Death's misty shadows
